<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  SpotBugs filter file.

  Scope so far: JPA entity collection exposure.

  ============================================================================
  EI_EXPOSE_REP / EI_EXPOSE_REP2 on `de.greluc.krt.profit.basetool.backend.model.*`
  ============================================================================

  Every JPA entity in this package exposes its `@OneToMany` / `@ManyToMany`
  collections via Lombok `@Getter` (and accepts them back via `@Setter`).
  SpotBugs and the `github-code-quality[bot]` running on PRs flag every such
  getter as "Exposing internal representation" â€” they keep counting because
  service code legitimately mutates the returned collections (the canonical
  `entity.getCollection().clear()` / `.add(x)` / `.remove(x)` / `.forEach(...)`
  pattern Hibernate manages via dirty-checking).

  The conventional SpotBugs fix is `Collections.unmodifiableSet(...)` in the
  getter plus a defensive-copy setter plus an `addXxx`/`removeXxx` helper API.
  That mechanically silences the rule but:

    1. The unmodifiable view would throw `UnsupportedOperationException` at
       every existing service call site â€” 12+ sites across `MissionService`,
       `JobOrderService`, `OperationService` would need refactoring to the
       new helper API.
    2. The `addXxx`/`removeXxx` helpers ultimately wrap the same `set.add()`
       call â€” the wrapper just hides the mutation behind a method name. The
       internal collection is still mutable; SpotBugs is happy because it
       can't see "through" the helper, but the real-world security posture
       is identical.
    3. Hibernate's dirty-checking depends on the persistent collection
       remaining the same managed instance throughout the transaction.
       Defensive-copy setters break the persistent-collection identity and
       can produce subtle dirty-checking misses.

  Architectural counter-argument: this project enforces "DTOs only at
  controller boundaries; never expose JPA entities at the HTTP boundary"
  (CLAUDE.md `Architecture > API conventions`), and the invariant is
  ArchUnit-enforced in
  `backend/.../ArchitectureTest.java`. No untrusted caller ever holds a
  reference to a managed entity, so the mutable collection cannot be reached
  from outside the `@Transactional` service layer.

  Per CLAUDE.md `Linting / static analysis`: a finding "may be silenced ...
  when the rule is genuinely wrong for that specific call site, and in that
  case leave a one-line comment explaining why." That's this whole block.

  If a future entity adds a collection that IS intended to be exposed
  immutably (e.g. a read-only audit log returned by a `/api/v1/<path>`
  endpoint that bypasses the DTO seam), tighten this filter at that point.
-->
<FindBugsFilter
    xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0"
    xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xsi:schemaLocation="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0 https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spotbugs/spotbugs/4.9.6/spotbugs/etc/findbugsfilter.xsd">

  <Match>
    <Class name="~de\.greluc\.krt\.profit\.basetool\.backend\.model\..*"/>
    <Or>
      <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP"/>
      <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP2"/>
    </Or>
  </Match>

  <!--
    ==========================================================================
    SPRING_CSRF_UNRESTRICTED_REQUEST_MAPPING on BasetoolErrorController
    ==========================================================================

    The error controller maps `${server.error.path:/error}` with a plain
    `@RequestMapping` (all HTTP methods) on purpose: the servlet container
    re-dispatches the ORIGINAL request method to the error path, so restricting
    it to GET would drop the RFC-7807 body for a POST/PUT/DELETE that errors.
    It is a read-only renderer â€” it reads the `jakarta.servlet.error.*`
    attributes and returns a problem+json body, mutating no state â€” so the
    CSRF-unrestricted-mapping detector is a false positive here (Spring Boot's
    own BasicErrorController, which this replaces, has the identical shape).
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="de.greluc.krt.profit.basetool.backend.controller.BasetoolErrorController"/>
    <Bug pattern="SPRING_CSRF_UNRESTRICTED_REQUEST_MAPPING"/>
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
